segments.text: Between the campus people and the Bryan people.
And what did they fight over?
Each one called each other names.
Did y'all have a favorite nickname for Bryan?
No.
You mostly had to go to
They had to go to Bryan because that's where all the car companies were.
And the banks.
The banks.
You had to make friends with those.
My father got awful mad at the First State Bank.
And I remember he went down there one day and parked in front of the First State Bank over on the side of the hill.
And he came walking out of there and he handed me this box.
He says, hold on to this for a few minutes.
And he backed the car out and went up the street to the city national bank.
And we made friends with Aston.
Now, there were then three banks, the first state, the first national, and the city national.
Now, the college, the fiscal department, they had some regulations within themselves.
Now, you could buy, they had a place.
See, Dad had the, Dad in the Aggie and New England, he had a filling station for the entire college.
That's where this building is built.
So that could any employee fill up their gas tank?
Oh, yeah.
They sold it just like a regular old filling station.
And then over there in another building, the milling part, the people that took care of the milling,
They had one you'd go over there and buy two or fours and all sorts of plumbing and fixtures.
Oh, really?
Okay.
Repair parts.
They carried most of the stuff that the college had to use, and then they had an open market right there.
Now, did the typical person who lived out here at college think of the Bryan people as stuck up,
No, there were an awful lot of people that came from Bryan to college, like it is now.
I don't know how many came from Caldwell.
But they still fought.
They still were— Well, they didn't fly.
They were rivals.
They were just rivals.
And if you lived out here, did you use the phrase, we live out at college?
No.
What did you say?
You lived at College Station.
You used the word station.
Back in the 20s?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, really?
Okay.
And it wasn't until Lankford got into it, Ernest Lankford, he was the one that was pushing the incorporation.
The incorporation.
And he did push it and did get a lot of it done.
All right, now let's go back.
You finished high school in what year?
And are you, at that point, you're sure you're going to college?
Oh, yeah.
As a matter of fact, Dad went over to Ernest Lankford
And he says, I don't know what he said to him.
He said, will you let Bill come up here?
At that time, the architecture was in the top of the administration building.
And you should come up here, and will you teach him?
Because I'd had, I'd already had, what do you call it, drawing.
Mechanical drawing?
Mechanical drawing.
In mechanical drawing, you draw this up here and you turn it like this.
In architecture, you slip it through and it makes it look a little sharper.
Now, when you finished... Ernest Langford got me, he made me work the techniques out.
In high school, had you been a good student?
On average, just average.
My biggest problem was with English.
I never was good with English.
And your strong courses were?
Shop courses.
Shop, engineering related?
Or science related.
It never bothered me.
When you started as a freshman in the fall of 31?
Yeah.
Did you plan to be an architect?
No.
I was going to be an ag engineer.
You were going to be an ag engineer.
Just like my father.
And where did you live as a freshman?
Oh, I lived at home.
You continued living at home?
Oh, it was what they now call a... A day duck?
Day duck.
But you were in the Corps.
Corps.
What outfit?
Coastal artillery.
uh and uh did you tell me about uh lining up to get your uniforms and all of that you were given some uniforms the biggest thing was the gun you were you checked out a rocket
What kind?
Cold action.
Springfield?
Springfield.
And where'd you keep it?
Well, they were up there in that department.
It was right where he got that big...
across from Kiko's right in there.
There was a bunch of steel buildings in there.
And you went over there and they checked you out of a rifle.
And I walked it back up there to the Ag Engineering Building right here.
And over in one corner of this thing we had a tub.
Here's a big thing.
And then about two or three hours later, I'd go down and clean it up.
Because that's something he wouldn't let all through that time.
He had to do that.
He couldn't just take the little rags and get it out.
All right.
Where did you register for classes?
Do you remember?
Did y'all line up in Sabeasa to register?
No.
I don't remember where the first place was.
That would be 31.
I don't remember where it was.
But later, it was a joke, because we'd be at home eating dinner.
And dad said across the table, he said, really, you want to register?
Yeah, I want to register.
I paid for it all.
I paid for it.
I made money, and I paid for everything.
It wasn't much.
And so we'd go up there wherever that registration was.
And he'd walk up to the door, and they had a guard there.
I'm taking this man to the dean.
He'd give me his cycle register and forget it.
Did some of your buddies tease you about having that kind of privilege?
No, they never knew anything about it.
Oh, okay.
Another privilege I had, too, you're supposed to wear a uniform when you went off campus.
I never wore one.
I've been down in Parker Ashton Hardware Company
My father was talking to the commandant, and I was right with him.
He would say that to me.
Who was the commandant when you were an undergraduate?
Oh, they had several of them.
They're just the head of the whole business.
During those first two years, describe your routine.
You got up at what time, ate breakfast at home,
But then did you have to come over and fall in with your outfit?
No.
No, they'd fall in.
I never did have to go to meals.
You had down military walls.
You had all those different outfits.
And then over here on this other one that went towards the depot,
There was another set there.
All right.
What had happened is when they started up, they all moved like that, company front.
And they were out there just like that.
But in drill, we used a drill on the drill field, if there was such.
They weren't really after me.
Were there other day ducks in your outfit?
Oh, yeah.
They were scattered all the way through there, not very many of them.
About how often did you come over and drill?
Once or twice a week?
Yeah, you had about two.
It's just like a class.
You didn't carry your gun.
So you got up at home, ate breakfast, put on your uniform.
and came to class, where'd you eat lunch?
Went back home.
Then in the afternoon, if you went to lab, you wore your uniform.
Yeah, unless they specified otherwise.
Do you remember what courses you took your freshman year?
Oh, I guess they were English.
I had to pull that thing.
Do you remember some of those early teachers?
Oh, well, no, not sure.
Well, you see, the first one I ever had was Ernest Langford.
Describe him, please, as a teacher.
Oh, he was great.
He was very particular about what he was trying to show you.
And I never had any trouble doing it, but I could do what he would ask me.
I'd been trained in handling pencils and stuff like that, you know.
My father gave me, I still got it in my library right there.
It's a German thing, it's all the instruments you need.
Right on the back of it says 1929.
That's when I got out of, I guess that's when I went to Bryan.
And did you make good grades that first year?
Oh, I made just ordinary grades.
But you didn't flunk out or flunk any courses or anything?
No, the only one I ever flunked was first grade.
It made me go back a second time, first grade.
When you started college, did your dad or anybody else give you any advice about college success?
No.
We lived there, and we were always in an academic atmosphere.
We were talking about stuff.
He'd tell me to go do something.
Here's another job I had.
The CE department had courses in the summertime where they surveyed a railroad from up here on the curve up there all the way to the river, a railroad and a road.
And Dad came to me one day and he says,
They need some help over there, over there.
And the Aggie and Nicaraguan had a flatbed IHC truck and four-cylinder engine.
And I knew how to drive that.
I drove it several times.
I was about 14 years old.
And he says, can you, would you want to go over there
and haul these things out there to the job site and then come back and get their lunch and haul that out there and come back and then come back in the evening.
I said sure.
I took that old truck and all, somewhere along, wherever they went out there.
I know that country out there just like the back of my hand because I had to find them.
And there was one old place out there that was a great big old, it was a pretty good sized Negro church.
And they had a big old bell up there in the front of it.
So I'd park over there and ring that bell.
And all those guys, it wasn't too far over there, they'd come walking over there.
But also the Negroes.
The Negroes.
And so they...
And Professor Ritchie was head of the department.
We ate with him and everything like that.
All the professors, they'd just sit down out there in some place, and we'd have lunch, and they had it out of their box.
I mean, the boxes.
They had two huge boxes bigger than these things here.
And they were on the back of the truck.
And I just backed up to the space hall, and they loaded them on.
And we tied them down.
We tied them down.
And then we'd go out there, and then the professors, when we were through with the meal, they had a container, another container, and they took all the sugar.
They wanted to make candy at the end of the season, so they took all the sugar.
There was usually five pounds of sugar in there.
And so then they just, they just, uh,
So they'd take that stuff and then the professors told me, when you go back to town, you stop at these nigger people and you get rid of that food.
And we don't want to send it back because they'll reduce the rations.
So I'd stop and tell those niggers, and I had a regular
Alright, now back here on the campus, how did you get indoctrinated into being an Aggie
as a day duck fish, did you all get hazed?
Did you get, what, give some examples.
We had, you always had, you had yell practices.
Okay.
On the steps of the YMCA.
Mm-hmm.
And the seniors stood around the outside of that thing, that whole thing, with that sandbond belt in their hand.
Mm-hmm.
And then?
You had to run it.
Oh, you had to run the circle?
No, you had to get out of there.
Oh, oh, oh, I see.
They had you hemmed up in there.
All right, but how did they instruct y'all in how to whip out and what to say and all that?
Where did you get that kind of?
Oh, that was done in, well, you had a,
You had a picture show, also.
Over in Guyon?
No.
Oh.
There were two of them.
Next to the, next to the O.F.A.
Chapel, this way, right beside the
two dormitories that were, I think they were torn down now.
But there were, there was, it was always right there.
A picture, a movie theater?
Yeah.
One they called the Air Dome.
Air Dome.
The Air Dome.
It was a building, just a big building come up like this.
And the projector was way in the back there.
And they had a screen up there on the, on the, on the
that they projected onto, and then the seats were just up off the floor.
They just, I don't know how they were built that way, but they were, every once in a while you'd have a set of planks.
They were just planks.
There was one for the feet and one for the butt coming across here.
like that, supported somehow.
But you could look underneath all that thing.
There was a big concrete flat.
And that was the air dome.
That was the early one.
Later, they tore that down, and they built the one, and it had, was built just like a regular theater was built.
It had, on the west side there, they had stage.
It wasn't much stage, but it was something.
Then you had a balcony all over around this thing like this, and then you had the whole floor under here was full of them.
Where was it located?
The same place where the air... Oh, where the air dome was.
They tore the air dome down and built this thing in there.
And...
So that's where they'd get you all together and
No, that's just where we had kind of a yell practice once in a while.
Or they'd get somebody up there and start to...
But the funny thing about that was, was Cuball Richie.
That's what they called him.
He was head of the, one of the guy I worked for.
He didn't have any hair, cue ball Richard.
He was head of the, you know, the strength of the chair, all the structural engineering, whatever it was, structural engineering.
Now the concrete was taught in a different place, but that,
You took strength and materials from him, you took things like that from him.
I actually had coated courses on him later on.
But he'd go to that, his wife was, had a disability or something, I don't know.
So this thing had two aisles in it like this and this whole thing in the middle was just a big mass of people.

right square in the middle of this out there and he'd park her down here on the edge of that and she was in the wheelchair he'd walk out there about the middle of that thing and sit down he turned some seats down around you and he sat there and he never bought a peanut yet they were pitching
Okay, okay.
He was out there, and he just showed like a, and everybody's pitching.
So he just reached over here in the seat and gave him some peanuts.
When, do you remember when A&M faculty didn't have nicknames?
Were the nicknames here when y'all got here?
I never knew or recall much of anything.
The only one we ever called or remember about was Dean Puryear.
What was he?
Pee-wee.
Pee-wee.
Because he was small?
Yeah.
Dean Pee-wee.
Well, and there's Bear Tracks Bolton.
I didn't ever know that.
Oh, really?
Bear Tracks Bolton.
That means something.
When he came in, he was in charge.
I think that's what they meant.
Did your dad have a nickname, as far as you know?
Dan?
And see, then when I get here, there's Screamin' Al Nelson in history.
Dr. Nance was Notes Nance.
D.B.
Cofer was Dusty Butt.
Because when he would erase the board, he would do this on his...
I had him, but I never did know that.
I had him, and then I had a fellow named Martin in English.
Did you and your buddies, did y'all ever get a paddle used on you?
No, I never did.
But the same brown belt sometimes.
You had to get out of that place down there.
You were running something.
You just ran like hell.
I tried to break out of that thing.
How did you and your buddies learn all of the minutia about the questions about A&M?
Where did you learn all that?
They never taught me anything.
I just knew what they were talking about.
They did...
theater there, they did a lot of singing, because a fellow by the name of Dunn was, and some other, the other people that made those songs, those were all made in about there.
You said Dunn, this is not J. Harold Dunn.
No, it's Carl Dunn.
Oh, oh, oh.
He was, he was
Oh, yeah, he was the, he directed the band for a long time, didn't he?
Yeah.
And he was, he had a daughter.
She was partially crippled or something.
You mentioned him.
Describe the Aggie band while you were a student.
It was good.
How big was it, I reckon?
Well, you're saying 200?
Was it that big?
I imagine it was.
Did they march well?
Oh, boy.
I mean, just kidding.
Were you Aggies proud of it?
You were proud of it.
And what were their halftime performances like?
Oh, they always made a tee.
They did?
They always made a tee.
Did they line up at the north end of Kyle Field to start?
They always gave the opposite of the people that...
Their opponents, the team, they had the halftime first.
They always gave them that.
They were quite gentle.
And the only trouble that they ever had was with Baylor.
Now, were there some problems with Baylor while you were a student?
Describe those, please.
Well,
They went up there to Baylor, the student body did.
Now the student body had what they called court trips.
And the whole thing tried to go.
And they also tried to try to get the railroads to give them a special car or something or a fare or something.
But they wouldn't go around.
So they would try to rent what they called a side door
A boxcar?
A boxcar.
But you got to realize that in that time, you see the automobile was coming in, and we got the thumb going this way, see?
And we had a special out there on that side.
You'd have a whole bunch of curlers standing up there, and some guy would stop and pick up, and your uniform was what counted.
Because when I came back from Brookings, I had my uniform.
I carried it with me.
I knew it.
I never, it did cost me a dime.
I went all the way home on some kind of a conveyance, another, never did ride as far as the truck did.
But back, back to the problems with Baylor.
Well, you see, they, they had uh, uh,
There was quite a lot of rivalry.
They brought a car, a Model T Ford, and they drove it onto the field during the halftime.
And it had painted on the outside of it all the scores where Baylor had beat A&M.
Oh, my.
Oh, my.
And they had taken some kids, and they looked, I don't know what they had.
They looked like they were girls.
I don't know whether they were.
They were driving it, you mean?
Yeah.
what they thought they were girls.
So the Corps went out there.
They just went out there.
And what they wanted to do, they were going to just pick that car up and escort it off of the field.
Well, it didn't turn out that way.
And a big fight ensued.
And the baler opened up.
had pieces of pipe in it, and that's what they were using.
And so the Cobra took that car, and I don't know how they did it, I've never knew that,
That car came the next day after that game.
It was in Speza Hall.
And all of this fight had occurred up at Waco.
Was anybody badly hurt in the fight?
